itle><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Singapore's central bank expected to tighten monetary policy, but could hold back if risk of tit-for-tat protectionism intensifies, say economists</Para><Para>Singapore</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>ESCALATING trade tensions between the United States and China could prompt Singapore's central bank to adopt a more cautious policy stance than it originally intended at its upcoming April meeting, economists say.</Para><Para>Market watchers were widely expecting the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) to tighten its Singdollar policy in response to improving growth and rising inflation. However, protectionist sabre-rattling by the world's two largest economies has shifted the needle.</Para><Para>If the risk of "tit-for-tat protectionism" intensifies in the coming weeks, Singapore's central bank could decide to hold back on policy tweaks.</Para><Para>The central bank uses the exchange rate as its main monetary policy tool to strike a balance between inflation from overseas and economic growth.</Para><Para>The rate is allowed to float within a band that can be adjusted when monetary policy is reviewed at biannual meetings in April and October.</Para><Para>A stronger currency - which corresponds to tighter monetary policy - counters inflation by making imports cheaper in Singapore dollar terms, while a weaker Singdollar helps lift growth by making exports cheaper abroad.</Para><Para>The SGD was marginally stronger at S$1.32 on March 24.</Para><Para>The exchange rate is managed against a basket of currencies of Singapore's major trading partners.</Para><Para>The Singdollar policy band is now on a path of zero appreciation against the currencies of key trading partners - a "neutral" stance put in place in April 2016 amid slow growth and low inflation. But times have changed.</Para><Para>The Singapore economy expanded 3.6 per cent last year with an upturn in global growth. This was faster than initial estimates and also picked up pace on 2016's 2.4 per cent.</Para><Para>An electronics boom propelled Singapore's export growth to a seven-year high last year, even as inflation turned positive for the first time since 2014.</Para><Para>In addition, core inflation - a key factor in monetary policy decisions - edged up to 1.7 per cent in February, the highest in more than three years.</Para><Para>Economists said this stronger outlook makes the case for tighter monetary policy, though any tweaks are likely to be gradual.</Para><Para>"We think MAS will likely normalise policy . . . The key word is normalisation, given the backdrop of a growth recovery with the re-emergence of some inflation risk," said Maybank Kim Eng economist Chua Hak Bin.</Para><Para>Bank of America Merrill Lynch economist Mohamed Faiz Nagutha noted: "The much-improved economic outlook and continuing recovery in the labour market make the case for policy tightening. There are also signs that inflation is likely to pick up gradually into the second half of 2018 and 2019.</Para><Para>"Unlike the past exits from neutral policy . . . the forthcoming exit will likely be more gradual to reflect the protracted recovery and the still-subdued inflationary environment."</Para><Para>But rising trade tensions between the US and China have thrown a spanner in the works given the potential impact on Singapore's small, open economy. US President Donald Trump announced on Thursday that he will slap about US$60 billion of tariffs on unspecified imports from China, with the list of targeted products set to be published in the coming days.</Para><Para>The new measures are aimed at penalising China for trade practices that the Trump administration says involve stealing American companies' intellectual property.</Para><Para>In addition, the administration has regularly highlighted China's US$375 billion surplus with the US as evidence of an unfair trade relationship.</Para><Para>In response, China said it was proposing additional tariffs on 128 US products valued at US$3 billion, even as it called on Washington to resolve the dispute through negotiations.</Para><Para>CIMB Private Bank economist Song Seng Wun said it is still too early to assess the potential impact of these developments on Singapore, given that the exact list of goods covered by the proposed US tariffs has yet to be released.</Para><Para>"As of now I would still say there is sufficient confidence that the MAS is ready to start on policy normalisation, because Singapore's economic fundamentals have improved sufficiently," he said. "That remains unchanged unless we see a real escalation in trade tensions over the next two weeks.</Para><Para>"China's measured, calibrated response suggests there's still wiggle room to avoid an all-out trade war."</Para><Para>Mr Chua said: "The risk of a full- blown trade war may defer MAS' decision to normalise, if the impact on trade and growth is perceived to be severe. (Still), we think the US and China would want to avoid a full- blown trade war, and some compromise will likely be struck in the coming months."</Para><Para>Added Mr Song: "If MAS were to put policy tweaks on hold citing increased risk of a trade war impacting Singapore, the market would not be surprised."</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Chia Yan Min , Caution the watchword as US-China trade tensions hang over MAS policy </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Market watchers were widely expecting the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) to tighten its Singdollar policy in response to improving growth and rising inflation. </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></